cs|1|ht|b|fp|1|cp|4|at|^-{  Checkback Stayman  }
^-|ht|D|fp||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Before going into detail about how to respond when partner opens one of a minor, I will discuss Checkback Stayman. This is because an understanding of Checkback Stayman is critical to the discussion of responses to one of a minor opening bids. |
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


AT|

Checkback Stayman is used by responder to discover whether an opener who has rebid 1N has either a 4 card major or 3 card support for a major previously bid by responder. The mechanics are simple. Over a 1N rebid by opener, if responder bids 2@C, that is Checkback Stayman (even if the opening bid was 1@C). If opener has a 4 card major, he bids it. Similarly, if opener has 3 card support for the major bid by responder, he bids it. If opener has neither, he bids 2@D.|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


AT| 

If opener has both a 4 card major and 3 card support, your partnership needs to decide what the rebid should be. The 3 choices are a) show the 3 card support, b) show the 4 card major, or c) always bid 2H. I personally have a slight preference for showing 3 card support (on the theory that you should "support with support" when you can), but all the choices are equally good. You just need to come to an agreement.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


 
HT|p|cs|6|cp|4|at|^b{|ia|,1cp1DP1NP2C|at|}|HT|p|CP||AT|^m@2For example, the auction on the left is Checkback Stayman, asking opener to show a 4 card major. |
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


HT|u|cs|6|cp|4|at|^b{|ia|,1DP1HP1NP2C|at|}|HT|u|CP||AT|^m@2Similarly, this auction is Checkback Stayman, asking opener to show either 3 card heart support (with 4 hearts opener would have raised hearts) or a 4 card spade suit. |
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


