cs|1|ht|b|fp|1|cp|4|at|^-{  2 way Checkback  }
^-|ht|D|fp||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Let me mention one other convention that some expert pairs play known as "2 way Checkback" or "2 way New Minor Forcing". If you play that, then both 2@C and 2@D over opener's 1NT rebid are conventional. Just as with regular Checkback, both are asking about opener's major suit holdings. |
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


AT|

2@D is game forcing Checkback whereas 2@C shows an invitational hand at best. The responses over 2@C are identical to those for regular Checkback. The responses over 2@D are more complicated (although opener's first obligation is still to show 3-card support or 4 cards in the other major). I won't go into further details here. The reason for playing this is basically the same as the reasons for playing 2 over 1 game forcing. Once responder bids 2@D, a game force has been established while the bidding is still at a low level. This gives the partnership a lot of room to explore for slam, including minor suit slams that would otherwise be hard to bid.|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


AT| 

